## 🧭 PROJECT CONTEXT

### Purpose
WinBoost is a Windows Batch (.bat) script that automates system cleaning, optimization, and repair in 4 sequential phases. It targets non-technical Windows users who want a one-click tool to speed up their PC, free disk space, and repair system file corruption without manually running multiple Microsoft tools.

### Goals
1. Clean all temporary files, caches, and junk from the system in a single run
2. Optimize network stack and RAM in a safe, reversible way
3. Apply performance tweaks (CPU plan, NTFS, startup delays) for immediate feel improvement
4. Repair Windows integrity using DISM with the best available image source, falling back gracefully

### Non-goals
- GUI or graphical interface (stays as CLI/Batch by design)
- Registry deep-cleaning beyond what is explicitly safe
- Removing user programs or personal files
- Scheduled / silent / background execution (requires explicit admin consent per run)
- Windows 7 / 8 / 8.1 support

### Target users
Non-technical Windows 10/11 users. They double-click the file, run as admin, and wait. They do not read logs unless something breaks.

### Key constraints
| Constraint | Detail | Impact |
|-----------|--------|--------|
| Admin required | All phases need elevated rights | Script exits early with instructions if not admin |
| Windows 10/11 only | Uses DISM, wevtutil, wsreset, powercfg | Do not use features absent in Win10 build 19041+ |
| No internet required | DISM must work offline if image is mounted | Always scan drives for local install.wim/esd first |
| No user data loss | Never touch Documents, Downloads, Desktop content | Only touch `%TEMP%`, `C:\Windows\Temp`, caches, logs |
| Batch only | No PowerShell scripts, no third-party tools | Use `powershell -Command` inline only for one-liners |

### Business / domain rules
- The papelera (Recycle Bin) is emptied without warning — documented in README FAQ.
- Browsers (Edge, Chrome, Firefox) are killed before cache cleaning — acceptable since script requires restart anyway.
- SysMain (Superfetch) is disabled assuming SSD. On HDDs this reduces performance — noted in README FAQ.
- DISM `/ResetBase` is irreversible: removes ability to uninstall Windows updates. This is intentional for space recovery.
- TCP/IP reset (`netsh winsock reset`, `netsh int ip reset`) invalidates VPN/proxy configs — documented.

### Assumptions
- The user is on a consumer SSD-based Windows 11 machine (most common target).
- Internet connection is available as DISM fallback if no local image is found.
- The user will restart after the script — all instructions say to restart.

