## 📐 CONVENTIONS

### Batch script conventions
| Element | Convention | Example |
|---------|-----------|---------|
| Phase headers | `echo  ====...====` then `echo   [ FASE N/4 ]  TITLE` | See any phase start |
| Step counters | `echo   [NN/TT] Description...` | `[01/18]`, `[2/7]` |
| Log entries | `echo   OK: description >> "%LOG_FILE%"` | After each step |
| Variables | ALL_CAPS with underscores | `WIN_BUILD`, `BEST_SOURCE` |
| Error suppression | `>nul 2>&1` on all system commands | Every `del`, `rd`, `reg`, `sc` |
| Log redirection | `>> "%LOG_FILE%" 2>&1` for verbose tools | DISM, SFC |
| Delayed expansion | `!VAR!` inside `for` loops and `if` blocks | All loop variable reads |
| Fallback pattern | Try best → try alt → log failure | DISM source selection |
| Section comments | `:: ====` header, `:: ----` subsection | See FASE 4 subsections |

### Phase order — NEVER change without updating README
1. FASE 1 — Limpieza profunda (file/cache deletion)
2. FASE 2 — Red y rendimiento (network, RAM, TRIM)
3. FASE 3 — Optimizacion avanzada (registry, CPU, services)
4. FASE 4 — Integridad (DISM, SFC) — ALWAYS LAST

### DISM source priority — enforced
1. Local `install.wim` with highest build number
2. Local `install.esd` with highest build number
3. Windows Update (no `/LimitAccess`)
4. Log failure if all fail

### Log format
- File created with `>` on init (overwrites any previous log with same timestamp — impossible collision)
- All subsequent writes use `>>`
- Format: plain text, no XML/JSON — human readable
- Location: `%USERPROFILE%\Desktop\WinBoost_Log_YYYYMMDD_HHMMSS.txt`

---

## ✅ CODE QUALITY

### Pre-output checklist for Batch code
- [ ] All `del`, `rd`, `reg`, `sc`, `net` commands end with `>nul 2>&1`
- [ ] Verbose tools (DISM, SFC) redirect with `>> "%LOG_FILE%" 2>&1`
- [ ] Each step has a corresponding `echo   OK: ... >> "%LOG_FILE%"` after it
- [ ] Variables inside `for` loops and `if` blocks use `!VAR!` not `%VAR%`
- [ ] All paths with spaces are quoted: `"%USERPROFILE%\..."`
- [ ] New steps added to the correct phase (see Enforced structure rules)
- [ ] Step counter `[NN/TT]` updated when adding steps to a phase
- [ ] README phase table updated when step count changes
- [ ] No interactive commands (`pause` is only at banner and final screen)
- [ ] Admin check at the top, not inline

### Forbidden patterns
- `del /s C:\` or `rd /s C:\` without specific subfolder — catastrophic
- `reg delete HKLM\...` without `>nul 2>&1` — shows ugly error on failure
- `wmic` without `2>nul` — can error on some configurations
- Hardcoded drive letters for user data (use `%USERPROFILE%`, `%LOCALAPPDATA%`, `%TEMP%`)
- Direct output to console from DISM/SFC without also writing to log
- `goto` labels except `:fin` (avoid spaghetti flow)
- Sleeping with `timeout` inside a phase for more than 2 seconds
- Any command that could delete from `%USERPROFILE%\Documents`, `\Desktop`, `\Downloads`

---

## 🔐 SECURITY

### Attack surface
| Surface | Risk | Mitigation |
|---------|------|-----------|
| Admin privilege | Script runs with SYSTEM-level power | Admin check is the first thing the script does |
| Path injection via env vars | `%TEMP%`, `%LOCALAPPDATA%` could be tampered | Quotes around all env var paths |
| DISM source path | User-mounted ISO could be malicious | Only reading standard `sources\install.wim` path; never executing from image |
| Shutdown command | `shutdown /r` at end | User must confirm with `choice /C SN`; defaults to No on timeout |
| Registry writes | Modifying HKCU and HKLM keys | Only well-documented performance keys; all use `/f` flag to avoid interactive prompts |

### Security forbidden patterns
- Never delete from paths provided by the user at runtime
- Never execute binaries found in discovered drives
- Never pipe DISM output to `eval` or execute it
- The DISM source is only PASSED as `/Source:` argument, never executed

---

## ⚡ PERFORMANCE

### Script runtime targets
| Phase | Expected time | Notes |
|-------|-------------|-------|
| FASE 1 | 1–5 min | Depends on disk size and browser cache |
| FASE 2 | < 1 min | Network resets are fast |
| FASE 3 | < 30 sec | Registry and powercfg are instant |
| FASE 4 | 10–40 min | DISM is the bottleneck; local image is 3–5× faster |
| Total | 15–45 min | |

### Performance rules for the script itself
- Do not add `timeout /t` inside phases except the 2s pause at phase end
- Use `for /d %%x in (...)` to delete directory trees, not recursive `del /s` when possible
- Prefer `wmic` for system info queries — faster than PowerShell process spawn
- DISM ScanHealth before RestoreHealth avoids full repair if system is clean

---

## 🧪 TESTING STRATEGY

### How to test
- Run in a Windows 10/11 VM with admin rights
- Check log file on Desktop after run
- Verify each phase header appears in the log
- Verify DISM source line shows correct image path if ISO was mounted
- Verify `:fin` label is reached cleanly (no orphaned processes)

### Test cases
| Test | Expected |
|------|---------|
| Run without admin | Error screen with instructions, `exit /b 1` |
| Run with admin, no ISO | DISM uses Windows Update |
| Run with admin, ISO mounted | DISM uses local image, log shows path |
| Run on system with no Chrome/Edge/Firefox | Steps skip silently, no errors |
| Run on system with all browsers open | Browsers are killed, caches cleaned |

---

## 🚨 ERROR HANDLING

### Error model
- Non-critical failures (e.g. a cache folder doesn't exist): `>nul 2>&1` suppresses, step marked OK
- DISM failure: 3-level fallback (local+LimitAccess → local without → Windows Update); log records which level succeeded
- SFC: runs unconditionally after DISM; output goes to log
- Admin check failure: immediate exit with user instructions
- `choice /C SN` at end: if user presses N or times out → `:fin` label, graceful exit

### Log-only failures
DISM and SFC errors are written to the log file but do NOT interrupt the script — the script always runs to completion. The user is told to check the log if something looks wrong.

